On this basis, mechanisms for the formation of different RTP of CDs@Al2O3 were proposed (Fig. 6f). Firstly, the rigid structure, stable strong covalent bonds and strong spatial confinement of porous Al2O3 effectively limited the vibrational loss of the luminescent center and the non-radiative leaps of the triplet excitons. Due to its small ΔE
                        ST, the CDs@Al2O3 composite undergoes ISC between S1 and the lowest triplet state T1, resulting in a long-lived RTP. Secondly, the core and surface states of CD were the two emission centers. For 500-CD@Al2O3 and 600-CD@Al2O3 composites, when the carbon nuclei were activated by high-energy excitation (285 nm), the excitons were first excited to the singly excited state (S1). Some of the excitons returned directly to the ground state (S0) by radiative leaps, producing strong fluorescence emission; due to the small single-heavy state-triple-excited state energy level difference (ΔEST
                        ) of the carbon nucleus, the S1 state could efficiently jump to the triple-excited state (T1) by the process of inter-system scampering (ISC), and the T1 state was subsequently returned to the ground state by radiative leaps (S0), which exhibited blue phosphorescence emission. Similarly, the carbonyl group of the surface state of CDs was activated at lower energy excitation (365 nm), and its electron-leap process was accompanied by both fluorescence and yellow-green phosphorescence emission [50–54]. An increase in temperature led to a decrease in the functional groups on the surface of the CDs and the aggregation of the CDs carbon nuclei, which changed the emission wavelength with respect to the phosphorescence lifetime. Following stimulation at 285 nm, 700-CDs@Al2O3 showed simultaneous activation of its two emission centers. Green phosphorescence was discharged at 500 nm by the carbon surface states, and blue phosphorescence was emitted at 425 nm by the carbon core. The blue phosphorescence decayed faster than green phosphorescence, thus showing a shift from blue phosphorescence to green phosphorescence. Furthermore, under visible light irradiation, the ground state electrons in the CDs@Al2O3 composite absorbed photon energy and jumped from the singlet state (S1) to the triplet state (T1) via an intersystem scrambling (ISC) process. Subsequently, the triplet excited state returned to the ground state (S0) via radiative excursion and released energy in the form of room-temperature yellow phosphorescence. Since sunlight contained both UV and visible light and the photon energy of UV light was higher than that of visible light, the composite emitted blue-green phosphorescence upon excitation by sunlight. [53].
